      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Click-through rate (CTR)</strong> is the percentage of people who click a link, ad, search result, or email out of everyone who saw it. The formula is <strong>(clicks divided by impressions) times 100</strong>. CTR is the single best indicator of how relevant, compelling, or well-positioned your creative is — higher CTR means the audience is responding to what they see.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Formula</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Clicks / Impressions × 100</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Analytics</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Google Ads avg</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3.17%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">CTR is the fastest feedback loop in marketing. You do not need a conversion to know if a headline is working — you can tell from the click. Which is why great marketers optimise CTR before they optimise anything downstream.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is click-through rate?</h2>
        <p>Click-through rate is the ratio of clicks to impressions on a piece of content, expressed as a percentage. An impression is any instance where the content was shown — a search result appearing on someone's screen, an ad served in a feed, or an email landing in an inbox. A click is a user actively pressing on that link.</p>
        <p>CTR is used across four dominant channels:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Organic search</strong> — clicks from a Google/Bing SERP divided by impressions in Search Console</li>
          <li><strong>Paid search</strong> — ad clicks divided by ad impressions in Google Ads or Microsoft Ads</li>
          <li><strong>Display and social ads</strong> — creative clicks divided by served impressions</li>
          <li><strong>Email marketing</strong> — unique clicks divided by delivered emails (not opens)</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Industry benchmark</div>
          <p>The organic-search #1 position captures roughly <strong>39.8% CTR</strong>. Position 10 drops to <strong>1.6%</strong>. That single curve is why teams spend six months and $100k to move from position 5 to position 1 — the click delta is nearly 6x.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why click-through rate matters</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>It is a relevance signal.</strong> Google's leaked NavBoost system uses click data to re-rank results. A page with above-position-average CTR often gets a boost; below-average CTR loses ground.</li>
          <li><strong>It drives Quality Score in paid.</strong> Google Ads uses expected CTR as one of three Quality Score inputs. Higher expected CTR lowers your cost-per-click.</li>
          <li><strong>It is your earliest optimisation lever.</strong> You can improve CTR by rewriting a title tag in 30 seconds — you cannot improve a conversion rate that fast.</li>
          <li><strong>It reveals content-audience fit.</strong> A high-ranking page with low CTR usually has a bad title or a mismatched intent, both of which are fixable without new content.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How CTR is calculated</h2>
        <p>The formula is the same everywhere. Divide clicks by impressions, multiply by 100.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Example calculation</span><br>
          Impressions:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="uf-status">10,000</span><br>
          Clicks:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="uf-new">340</span><br>
          <br>
          CTR = (340 / 10,000) × 100<br>
          CTR = <span class="uf-status">3.4%</span>
        </div>

        <p>What counts as an "impression" varies by platform. Search Console counts an impression when your URL appears anywhere in the SERP the user sees. Google Ads counts an impression only when the ad is served. Email tools count it as any delivered send (not opens).</p>

        <h2 id="types">CTR benchmarks by channel</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
