              <tr><td><strong>Email marketing</strong></td><td>2.6%</td><td class="cell-yes">4%+ is strong</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>LinkedIn Ads</strong></td><td>0.44%</td><td class="cell-meh">0.8%+ is strong</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real CTR examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Rewriting a title tag</h3>
        <p>A law firm ranked #4 for "car accident lawyer austin" with a title of <code>Smith &amp; Associates — Personal Injury Firm</code>. CTR sat at 2.1%. Rewriting to <code>Car Accident Lawyer Austin · Free Consult, No Win No Fee</code> lifted CTR to 7.8%. No ranking change; the traffic tripled.</p>

        <h3>2. Adding rich results</h3>
        <p>An e-commerce category page ranked #3 for "wireless earbuds under 100". Adding Product schema surfaced review stars in the SERP. CTR moved from 4.2% to 6.9% — a 64% lift with zero content changes.</p>

        <h3>3. Rewriting an ad headline</h3>
        <p>A SaaS company ran <code>Learn More About Our Tool</code> at 2.7% CTR. Testing <code>See dashboard in 30 seconds</code> against it doubled CTR to 5.1% and dropped CPC by 22% via Quality Score.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">CTR vs conversion rate — which to optimise</h2>
        <p>Both matter. CTR is a top-of-funnel efficiency measure; conversion rate is what happens after the click. Optimise CTR when impressions are cheap and clicks are the bottleneck. Optimise conversion rate when clicks are expensive and drop-off is the bottleneck.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Optimise CTR when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You have plenty of impressions but few clicks</li>
              <li>You want to lower CPC via Quality Score</li>
              <li>Organic position is stuck but rankings are decent</li>
              <li>You are testing headlines, subject lines, or thumbnails</li>
              <li>Email opens are strong but link clicks are weak</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Optimise conversion rate when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Clicks are high but purchases/signups are not</li>
              <li>CPC is already low and further CTR gains cost too much</li>
              <li>Landing-page bounce rate is the visible problem</li>
              <li>Your traffic is high-intent (branded search)</li>
              <li>You have a proven offer but weak on-page copy</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for improving CTR</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Front-load benefit in the title.</strong> The first 55 characters carry the click. Lead with the outcome the reader wants.</li>
          <li><strong>Add numbers and brackets.</strong> "7 ways", "in 2026", "[Free Template]" all lift CTR by making the result feel specific.</li>
          <li><strong>Add rich results with structured data.</strong> Review stars, FAQ dropdowns, and Product snippets lift CTR 20-30% at the same position.</li>
          <li><strong>Rewrite meta descriptions quarterly.</strong> Google rewrites them anyway, but a strong original description gets shown 60-70% of the time.</li>
          <li><strong>Match search intent exactly.</strong> A query looking for a definition wants a definition — not a product page. CTR punishes intent mismatches.</li>
          <li><strong>Segment Search Console by query.</strong> Pages with 100+ impressions and CTR below the position average are the biggest opportunities.</li>
          <li><strong>Test one variable at a time.</strong> Rewrite the title OR the description OR the URL — not all three. You need to know which change moved the needle.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — clickbait CTR</div>
          <p>Titles that overpromise lift CTR temporarily but crush downstream conversions and increase pogo-sticking. Google's user-interaction signals then push the page back down. High CTR only helps if the click satisfies the user.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common CTR mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Comparing CTR without adjusting for position.</strong> A 5% CTR at position 10 is amazing; 5% at position 1 is terrible.</li>
          <li><strong>Averaging CTR across the whole site.</strong> Segment by page or query — sitewide averages hide the real problem pages.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the intent behind the query.</strong> Informational queries have lower CTRs than transactional ones. Both are fine.</li>
          <li><strong>Chasing branded CTR benchmarks.</strong> Branded search always converts higher — do not benchmark non-branded pages against it.</li>
          <li><strong>Not accounting for AI Overviews.</strong> Since 2024, Google's AI Overviews absorb clicks that used to hit organic. Absolute CTR dropped 20-40% on many informational queries.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
